+      "title": "When Trust in AI Goes Up, Verification Goes Down",
+      "content": "Microsoft Research published a survey of 319 knowledge workers in early 2025, asking how generative AI changes the work of thinking. The team logged 936 task instances and asked workers what they did, what AI did, and how their cognitive effort shifted. Two findings define the result.\n\nFirst, AI use does not eliminate cognitive work. It moves it. Workers who used generative AI reported less effort gathering and synthesizing information, and more effort verifying AI output, integrating AI-produced content into their own thinking, and managing the model's responses. The labor migrates upstream into prompt design and downstream into verification. Workers described a new demand: judging whether an AI draft was ready to ship before they passed it on.\n\nSecond, and this is the finding Week 6 should carry: the more confident a worker was in the AI's output, the less critical thinking they reported applying. Trust correlated with reduced verification. Self-confidence ran the opposite way. Workers who trusted their own expertise on the task verified more, regardless of how clean the AI's draft looked. Self-confidence beat AI-confidence as a predictor of who actually checked the work.\n\nFor DC CAP, this is the Week 6 challenge in survey form. Diligence sits with the user. The pilot's verification habits live or die on whether a coach or a director reads Claude's clean draft as a finished product or as a candidate that needs review. The cleaner the draft looks, the more carefully you have to read it. Confidence works as the variable that quietly removes Diligence from the workflow when no one builds the check in.",
+      "tryThis": "Pick the Claude output you trusted most this week. Re-read it as if a colleague drafted it without your context. Find one claim you accepted without checking. Verify it. Write into your trace whether the verification changed the draft. Confidence is the variable. Verification is the lever you control.",
+      "date": "2026-05-14",
+      "publishedDate": "2026-05-14",
+      "resource": "https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/publication/the-impact-of-generative-ai-on-critical-thinking-self-reported-reductions-in-cognitive-effort-and-confidence-effects-from-a-survey-of-knowledge-workers/",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Microsoft Research published a survey of 319 knowledge workers in early 2025 examining how generative AI changes cognitive work | Source: VERIFIED (Lee, Sarkar, Tankelevitch, Drosos, Rintel, Banks, Wilson, \"The Impact of Generative AI on Critical Thinking: Self-Reported Reductions in Cognitive Effort and Confidence Effects from a Survey of Knowledge Workers,\" CHI 2025, Microsoft Research)\nClaim: 936 task instances analyzed | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — survey collected 936 real-world task instances from the 319 respondents)\nClaim: AI use does not eliminate cognitive work; it shifts effort from information gathering to verification, integration, and response management | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — findings on shift in cognitive labor from gathering/synthesizing to evaluating AI output, integrating it, and overseeing the model)\nClaim: Higher confidence in the AI's output was associated with less self-reported critical thinking | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — central finding that higher trust in GenAI predicts reduced critical thinking effort)\nClaim: Higher self-confidence in one's own expertise was associated with more critical thinking, regardless of AI output quality | Source: VERIFIED (same paper — corresponding finding that self-efficacy increases critical thinking effort during AI-assisted work)\nClaim: Week 6 of the pilot focuses on Diligence — verifying AI output before it ships externally | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html, Week 6 Challenge: \"Find one output you sent externally this week. Trace it like the example above: what did Claude produce, what did you change, and why? Bring the trace to Friday.\")\nClaim: Diligence is one of the four fluency dimensions in the pilot framework (Delegation, Description, Discernment, Diligence) | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html, AI Fluency Framework, 4D model)\nEditorial: \"Diligence sits with the user\" and \"The cleaner the draft looks, the more carefully you have to read it\"